.5&amp;fp-y=0.5&amp;h=1333&amp;q=75&amp;w=2000&amp;s=d53950735f0eeef70ed995b579d38f0b 2000w"
                    />

            
    
<figcaption class="attribution">
        <span class="attribution__caption">Don Ledgerwood hauls clean water from a well at his son and daughter-in-law’s home.</span>
    
        <span class="attribution__credit">
        <span class="a11y">Credit: </span>
        Mark Olalde/ProPublica
    </span>
    
    
    </figcaption>

</figure>

        
    
                    
<p data-pp-blocktype="copy" data-pp-id="100.0">Don’s back is slightly hunched, but his sprightliness belies his 84 years. He still cuts the expanse of grass surrounding his old brick house, and Stan long ago gave up asking to do it for him. “He doesn’t do it right,” Don said, as he filled 5-gallon blue plastic jugs with water from Stan’s well. In one form or another, Don has been hauling water for six years.</p>
        
    
